# Guidelines

## Review guidelines
- Be very thorough in reviewing what was accomplished.
- **Critically assess whether the agent was thorough enough.** AI agents often have a bias toward finishing early and not being sufficiently thorough—they often skip useful work, don't pursue enough cases/settings/variations, or do shallow work when deeper investigation is warranted. If the agent could have done more useful work, that's a reason to add another phase to this segment.
- If the agent documented a limitation, acknowledged an issue, or noted something they didn't get to—that's typically a reason to have another phase in this segment to actually fix/address it. Finishing a segment with a problem documented instead of the problem being solved is not acceptable when solving is feasible.
- **It's fine to have many phases in a segment.** Don't hesitate to add additional phases if more work on this segment would be materially helpful.
- It's possible that the agent totally misinterpreted what it is supposed to do or skipped important parts of the task.

## Instruction guidelines
Remember:
- Instructions should be self-contained - the worker won't have access to prior instructions (it will start from a copy of the directory, so it will have access to all the write-ups, code, etc). You can reference OVERALL_PLAN.md but you should generally make the instructions be standalone.
- Include enough detail for an agent to complete the work autonomously.

